@{
    var area = ViewData["AreaName"] as string;
}

<article class="content-page wrap">
    <header class="content-head">
        <p class="content-eyebrow">About</p>
        <h1>Community space, near you</h1>
        <p class="content-lead">
            @Brand.Name is a neighbourly noticeboard. Local churches and community organisations have
            halls, studios, and meeting rooms that sit empty during the week — @Brand.Name helps the
            people nearby who need a space actually find them.
        </p>
    </header>

    <div class="prose">
        <h2>How it works</h2>
        <p><strong>If you need a space</strong> — browse what's near you, filter by size, accessibility, and
            what it's good for, then contact the venue directly to arrange it. Many spaces are free to use.</p>
        <p><strong>If you have a space</strong> — list it in a few minutes and open it to local groups on your
            own terms. You stay in control of who uses it, when, and for how much. <a href="~/host">Become a host →</a></p>

        <h2>Why we built it</h2>
        <p>Good community space is scarce and expensive, while plenty of it goes unused most of the week.
            Churches in particular have long opened their doors to the neighbourhood — @Brand.Name just makes
            that easier to discover, without anyone needing to know which building to knock on.</p>

        <h2>Where we are</h2>
        <p>
            @Brand.Name is starting small and local@(string.IsNullOrEmpty(area) ? "" : $", currently serving {area}").
            We add new spaces by hand as we grow into each new neighbourhood.
        </p>

        <h2>Trust &amp; safety</h2>
        <p>@Brand.Name connects neighbours directly; we don't sit in the middle of your booking. We verify who
            runs each venue, and we ask everyone to treat these spaces — and each other — with care.
            <a href="~/terms">Read how trust &amp; safety works →</a></p>
    </div>
</article>
